    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec 27. 1877</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am much obliged to you for kindly informing me of the case of the goose. It seems to be a remarkable case of inheritance of effects of injury &amp; as such cases are very rare it would be quite worth while to have the parts carefully examined. If you could obtain a wing &amp; would send it me I should be much obliged.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The wing might be cut off at the joint with the body &amp; dried with feathers on before a hot fire. To make the case of more value it would be very advisable to ascertain whether the goose had any offspring before the injury, &amp; if so whether they were normal &amp; not malformed in any way.</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Blair’s letter to CD has not been found; it was later sent to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1670.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Henry Flower</ref> together with a specimen of the wing, and Flower returned the letter with a sketch of the wing drawn on the back (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 26, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11375.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. H. Flower, 25 February 1878</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11471.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. H. Flower, 12 April 1878</ref>). CD was sceptical about the inheritance of injuries, but had reported some cases in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 2: 22–4; CD had expanded this section in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7952.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 2d ed.</ref> 1: 466–70.</note> 
        </div>
    
